ns who most need high-quality health care and social services have the greatest difficulty accessing them. Achieving good health is not simply a matter of making the right choices as an individual, the research demonstrates: it’s the product of large-scale political and economic forces. Understanding these forces, and what we can do to correct them, should be critical not only to doctors but to sociologists and students of the urban environment—and no city offers more inspiring examples for action to overcome social injustice in health than Chicago.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aMedical carezIllinoiszChicagoxSocial aspects. 0aMinoritiesxMedical carezIllinoiszChicago. 7aMEDICAL / General.2bisacsh  aChicago.  aactivism.  acommunity.  adiscrimination.  aequity.  ahealth.  ahospital.  aprotest.  aracism.1 aAbraham, Laurie Kaye, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAllen, Karen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAnsell, David A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAnsell, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAnsell, MD, David A., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBalch, George, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBenbow, Nanette, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlack, Edwin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrasel, Karen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrennan, Robert T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBuka, Stephen L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurgess-Bishop, Jacqueline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/voca